<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Mathematical_results">Mathematical results</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=G%C3%A1bor_Tardos&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1" title="Edit section: Mathematical results">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>Tardos started with a result in <a href="/wiki/Universal_algebra" title="Universal algebra">universal algebra</a>: he exhibited a maximal <a href="/wiki/Clone_(algebra)" title="Clone (algebra)">clone</a> of monotone operations which is not finitely generated. He obtained partial results concerning the <a href="/wiki/Hanna_Neumann_conjecture" title="Hanna Neumann conjecture">Hanna Neumann conjecture</a>. With his student, <a href="/wiki/Adam_Marcus_(mathematician)" title="Adam Marcus (mathematician)">Adam Marcus</a>, he proved a combinatorial conjecture of <a href="/wiki/Zolt%C3%A1n_F%C3%BCredi" title="Zoltán Füredi">Zoltán Füredi</a> and <a href="/w/index.php?title=P%C3%A9ter_Hajnal&amp;action=edit&amp;redlink=1" class="new" title="Péter Hajnal (page does not exist)">Péter Hajnal</a> which was known to imply the <a href="/wiki/Stanley%E2%80%93Wilf_conjecture" title="Stanley–Wilf conjecture">Stanley–Wilf conjecture</a>. With topological methods he proved that if <img class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline tex" alt="\mathcal{H}" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/5/0/350860cf68ca8fd18af87b6ee9044fc7.png" /> is a finite set system consisting of the unions of intervals on two disjoint lines, then <img class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline tex" alt="\tau(\mathcal{H})\leq 2\nu(\mathcal{H})" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/b/b/1bb37e7ab80e19e0325d7fd95d3db267.png" /> holds, where <img class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline tex" alt="\tau(\mathcal{H})" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/b/3/3b3e171d4963afabe37617d7fabfffae.png" /> is the least number of points covering all elements of <img class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline tex" alt="\mathcal{H}" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/5/0/350860cf68ca8fd18af87b6ee9044fc7.png" /> and <img class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline tex" alt="\nu(\mathcal{H})" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/f/7/7f75cf407db65c83e17c190891d07b19.png" /> is the size of the largest disjoint subsystem of <img class="mwe-math-fallback-image-inline tex" alt="\mathcal{H}" src="//upload.wikimedia.org/math/3/5/0/350860cf68ca8fd18af87b6ee9044fc7.png" />. Tardos worked out a method for optimal probabilistic fingerprint codes. Although the mathematical content is hard, the algorithm is easy to implement.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Awards">Awards</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=G%C3%A1bor_Tardos&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2" title="Edit section: Awards">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<p>He received the European Mathematical Society prize for young researchers at the <a href="/wiki/European_Congress_of_Mathematics" title="European Congress of Mathematics">European Congress of Mathematics</a> in 1992 and the <a href="/wiki/Paul_Erd%C5%91s_Prize" title="Paul Erdős Prize">Erdős Prize</a> from the <a href="/wiki/Hungarian_Academy_of_Sciences" title="Hungarian Academy of Sciences">Hungarian Academy of Sciences</a> in 2000. He received a Lendület Grant from the Hungarian Academy of Sciences (2009).<sup id="cite_ref-2" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-2"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup> specifically devised to keep outstanding researchers in Hungary.</p>
<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Selected_publications">Selected publications</span><span class="mw-editsection"><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href="/w/index.php?title=G%C3%A1bor_Tardos&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3" title="Edit section: Selected publications">edit</a><span class="mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></h2>
<ul>
<li><cite id="CITEREFTardos2008" class="citation">——— (2008), "Optimal probabilistic fingerprint codes", <i><a href="/wiki/Journal_of_the_ACM" title="Journal of the ACM">Journal of the ACM</a></i> <b>55</b>, <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//dx.doi.org/10.1145%2F780542.780561">10.1145/780542.780561</a></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AG%C3%A1bor+Tardos&amp;rft.atitle=Optimal+probabilistic+fingerprint+codes&amp;rft.aufirst=G.&amp;rft.aulast=Tardos&amp;rft.date=2008&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1145%2F780542.780561&amp;rft.jtitle=Journal+of+the+ACM&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.volume=55" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span>.</li>
<li><cite id="CITEREFTardos1995" class="citation">——— (1995), "Transversals of 2-intervals, a topological approach", <i><a href="/wiki/Combinatorica" title="Combinatorica">Combinatorica</a></i> <b>15</b>: 123–134, <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//dx.doi.org/10.1007%2Fbf01294464">10.1007/bf01294464</a></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AG%C3%A1bor+Tardos&amp;rft.atitle=Transversals+of+2-intervals%2C+a+topological+approach&amp;rft.aufirst=G.&amp;rft.aulast=Tardos&amp;rft.date=1995&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1007%2Fbf01294464&amp;rft.jtitle=Combinatorica&amp;rft.pages=123-134&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.volume=15" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span>.</li>
<li><cite id="CITEREFTardosBen-DavidBorodinKarp1994" class="citation">———; Ben-David, S.; Borodin, A.; <a href="/wiki/Richard_Karp" title="Richard Karp" class="mw-redirect">Karp, R.</a>; <a href="/wiki/Avi_Wigderson" title="Avi Wigderson">Wigderson, A.</a> (1994), "On the power of randomization in on-line algorithms", <i><a href="/wiki/Algorithmica" title="Algorithmica">Algorithmica</a></i> <b>11</b>: 2–14, <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//dx.doi.org/10.1007%2Fbf01294260">10.1007/bf01294260</a></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AG%C3%A1bor+Tardos&amp;rft.atitle=On+the+power+of+randomization+in+on-line+algorithms&amp;rft.au=Ben-David%2C+S.&amp;rft.au=Borodin%2C+A.&amp;rft.aufirst=G.&amp;rft.au=Karp%2C+R.&amp;rft.aulast=Tardos&amp;rft.au=Wigderson%2C+A.&amp;rft.date=1994&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1007%2Fbf01294260&amp;rft.jtitle=Algorithmica&amp;rft.pages=2-14&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.volume=11" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span>.</li>
<li><cite id="CITEREFTardos1986" class="citation">——— (1986), "A maximal clone of monotone operations which is not finitely generated", <i><a href="/wiki/Order_(journal)" title="Order (journal)">Order</a></i> <b>3</b>: 211–218, <a href="/wiki/Digital_object_identifier" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="//dx.doi.org/10.1007%2Fbf00400284">10.1007/bf00400284</a></cite><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AG%C3%A1bor+Tardos&amp;rft.atitle=A+maximal+clone+of+monotone+operations+which+is+not+finitely++generated&amp;rft.aufirst=G.&amp;rft.aulast=Tardos&amp;rft.date=1986&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1007%2Fbf00400284&amp;rft.jtitle=Order&amp;rft.pages=211-218&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.volume=3" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span>.</li>
